Olympics 2016 Analytics

The Rio 2016 Olympics was a landmark event, marking the first time the Olympic Games were hosted in South America. Held in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, from August 5 to 21, 2016, the event brought together athletes from across the globe, competing in a wide array of sports. The games featured a mix of traditional Olympic sports and newer ones like rugby sevens and golf, drawing attention from millions worldwide.

| Dataset Overview¶

| Features¶


  1. ID [numeric]: A unique identifier for each athlete.
  2. Name [categorical]: The full name of the athlete.
  3. Nationality [categorical]: The nationality of the athlete, indicating their country of origin.
  4. Sex [categorical]: The gender of the athlete (M for Male, F for Female).
  5. DOB (Date of Birth) [Date]: The birthdate of the athlete.
  6. Height [numeric]: The height of the athlete (in meters).
  7. Weight [numeric]: The weight of the athlete (in kilograms).
  8. Sport [categorical]: The sport in which the athlete competed.
  9. Gold, Silver, Bronze [categorical]: These columns indicate the number of gold, silver, and bronze medals won by the athlete.

In [73]:
top_countries_dict = {}

# Loop through each unique sport and get the top 3 countries
for sport in df['sport'].unique():
    sport_df = df[df['sport'] == sport]
    top_countries = sport_df.groupby('nationality')[['gold', 'silver', 'bronze']].sum().sort_values(by=['gold', 'silver', 'bronze'], ascending=False).head(3)
    top_countries_dict[sport] = ', '.join(top_countries.index)

# Convert the dictionary to a dataframe
top_countries_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(top_countries_dict, orient='index', columns=['Top 3 Countries'])

top_countries_df.style.background_gradient(cmap='Purples')

# Get the top athletes ranked by gold, silver, and bronze medals
top_athletes = (
    df.groupby('name')
    [['gold', 'silver', 'bronze']]
    .sum()
    .assign(total_medals=lambda x: x['gold'] + x['silver'] + x['bronze'])
    .sort_values(['gold', 'silver', 'bronze'], ascending=False)
    .reset_index()
    .reset_index(drop=False)
    .rename(columns={'index': 'rank'})
)

def plot_histogram(data, column_name, bins=20, kde=True, alpha=1):
    sns.histplot(data[column_name], bins=bins, kde=kde, alpha=alpha, color = '#f0de7d')

    plt.title(f'{column_name} Distribution')
    plt.xlabel(column_name)
    plt.ylabel('Density')

    plt.show()

# Create a figure with two subplots
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 6))

# Group by 'sex' and calculate mean 'height'
mean_heights = df.groupby('sex')['height'].mean()

# Plot average height
colors = {'male': '#6e6d6d', 'female': '#fe346e'}
mean_heights.plot(kind='bar', color=[colors[sex] for sex in mean_heights.index], ax=ax[0])
ax[0].set_ylabel('Height')
ax[0].set_title('Average Height by Sex (2016 Olympics)')

# Group by 'sex' and calculate mean 'weight'
mean_weights = df.groupby('sex')['weight'].mean()

# Plot average weight
mean_weights.plot(kind='bar', color=[colors[sex] for sex in mean_weights.index], ax=ax[1])
ax[1].set_ylabel('Weight')
ax[1].set_title('Average Weight by Sex (2016 Olympics)')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

sns.kdeplot(data=df[df['sex'] == 'female']['height'], color='pink', fill=True, label='Females', ax=axs[0])
axs[0].set_xlabel('Height')
axs[0].set_ylabel('Density')
axs[0].set_title('Male vs Female Heights, Olympics 2016')
axs[0].legend()
